    As the name suggests, the `reverse()` method reverses the order of all the characters in the string but does not change their case or other attributes. So if our initial string has both capitalized and small letters along with numbers and special characters, they would remain unchanged after calling the `reverse()` method.
    To fix this issue, we need to first convert our entire string into either uppercase or lowercase before passing it to the `reverse()` method. Then again, we may want to revert back to the previous state so that we don’t lose information about the original string. For this purpose, we can make use of another method called `toUpperCase()`. It converts the whole string to uppercase while maintaining the case of individual words intact. Similarly, there exists a similar method called `toLowerCase()`, which converts the whole string to lowercase without affecting the case of individual words.
    Now, let us see what happens when we pass our string through these methods.
    If we call `toUpperCase()` on “abc”, we get “ABC”. However, if we do the same thing on “AbC”, we get “ABc”. Thus, the second letter becomes smaller than the third one.
    Likewise, if we call `toLowerCase()` on “ABC”, we get “abC”. But if we do the same thing on “aBC”, we get “abc”. Again, the second letter becomes bigger than the third one.
    Now, since we know that the `reverse()` method doesn’t change the case of the individual words, we can safely assume that it won’t change them even after converting the whole string to uppercase or lowercase. Therefore, we can simply apply the two conversion methods sequentially and then call the `reverse()` method.
